passages.text: F4Q25 Recap: Record Notional Volume Growth; FY26 Guidance Ahead on Markety Metrics

GMV growth exceeded \(40\%\) for the first time since the pandemic, and notional volume growth reached the highest level on record, capping off a strong FY25. Looking ahead, notional FY26 GMV and RLTC guidance were a touch ahead of Street estimates, signaling another year of \(>20\%\) RLTC growth, and profitability targets (both GAAP and non- GAAP) were comfortably ahead of JPM and Street, which is encouraging. We are tweaking estimates and raising our Dec. '26 PT to \(\) 94\(from\) \ \(91\) . We reiterate our OW rating. See details within.

FY26 Guidance Summary. Mgmt guided to \(>\) 46bn in FY26 GMV, which was a touch ahead of Street estimates ( \(45.8bn\) ). We note take rate (guidance/ Street at \(\sim 8.4\% /8.5\%\) ) and notional revenue (guidance/Street at \(>\) 3,864M/ \(\) 3,900M\(guidance were a touch below expectations, but RLTC margin, adj. operating margin and GAAP operating margin guidance all came in above prior Street estimates, which is encouraging. Specifically, Mgmt forecasts\) \sim 4.0\% \(RLTC margin (flat y/y and towards the high end of its target range),\) >26.1\% \(adj. operating margin (up\) >200bps \(y/y\) and \(>6.0\%\) GAAP operating margins (up \(>800bps\) y/y) in FY26. Additionally, Affirm has a history of beating and raising guidance throughout the year. We note FY25 and FY24 GMV ended up coming in \(9\% (-\) 3.2bn) and \(11\% (-\) 2.6bn) ahead of guidance first provided on the F4Q call.

Notes from the Call. (1) \(0\%\) loans (including Pay- in- X and long- term \(0\%\) increased \(66\% y/y\) to a record \(\) 3.0bn\(. Interestingly, though only accounting for\) 29\% \(of GMV, half of all new - to - Affirm users initially transacted with a\) 0\% \(APR product, demonstrating its importance as a customer acquisition tool. (2) Guidance assumes Affirm will be removed from the Walmart website by the start of F2Q26, though a portion of its Walmart volume today is originated from the Affirm app ( \(- 1 / 3rd\) ), which could continue moving forward. (3) Credit trends remain solid, as \(30+\) day DQs (ex- Peloton & Pay- in- X) declined 15bps q/q and 18bps y/y, partially owed to mix shift towards \(0\%\) APR products (which typically have a lower credit risk profile than interest bearing loans).

F3Q25 Recap. GMV increased \(43\% y/y\) (JPM and Street at \(32\%\) ), accelerating 7pt sequentially, directionally consistent with broader payment/e- comm trends. Take rate \((8.5\%)\) was a touch below Street \((8.7\%)\) for the second consecutive quarter, primarily on GMV mix- shift towards \(0\%\) APR loans, though RLTC margin \((4.1\%)\) was aligned with JPM/Street estimates. Adj oping margin was \(26.9\%\) , comfortably ahead of the high end of the guide \(25\%\) ) and Street estimates \((24.7\%)\) . AFIM also reported its first quarter of GAAP operating profitability, marking a nice milestone. See Table 1 and Table 2, within.

Model Update. We are updating estimates to reflect FY26 guidance, specifically increased mix- shift towards \(0\%\) APR loans (which is take rate dilutive) and continued \(>25\%\) GMV growth. Our FY26 and FY27 RLTC estimates move to \(\) 1.9bn\(from\) \ \(1.7bn\) and \(\) 2.3bn\(from\) \ \(2.1bn\)

AFRM provides digital point-of-sale financing for some of the most iconic brands, marketplaces, and platforms and has become a market proxy for the once white-hot BNPL space. We expect Affirm to deliver premium volume growth (>20%) and expanding operating margins for the foreseeable future, driven by increased penetration at the company's platform partners (Shopify, Amazon, Apple Pay) and continued growth in its rapidly scaling Direct to Consumer business (Affirm Card). We rate shares OW with a $94 Dec '26 price target.

Affirm shares are extremely volatile, trading between 3.0-7.0x NTM revenue over the last year alone, and currently trade at 6.3x. We are raising estimates, and our Dec. '26 PT moves to $94 (from $91), applying a 6.5x P/S (14.0x P/gross profit) multiple to our CY27E revenue forecast ($5.4bn, up from $5.1bn). Our revised target multiple is toward the high end of AFRM's recent range, which we think is reasonable and warranted given underlying business momentum, GAAP profitability targets,and the potential for greater operating leverage. We reiterate our OW rating.

RLTC margin declined 20bps y/y to \(4.1\%\) , which was consistent with JPM/e/Street estimates. Adj operating margin was \(26.9\%\) , which was comfortably ahead of JPM and Street \((24.7\%)\) estimates. See details below.

Card volume surpassed \$1bn for the first time ever, and spend per cardholder increased \(21\%\) y/y to \(\sim \$ 511\) in the quarter, representing the highest level since F2Q24. See details below.

Mqmt guided to \(>\) 46bn in FY26 GMV, which was a touch ahead of Street estimates \((\) 45.8bn). That said, take rate (guidance/Street at \(\sim 8.4\% /8.5\%)\) and notional revenue (guidance/Street at \(\sim\) 3,864M/3,900M) were a touch below expectations. Encouragingly, though, RLTC margin, adj. operating margin and GAAP operating margin guidance all came in above prior Street estimates. Specifically, Mqmt expects \(\sim 4.0\%\) RLTC margin (flat y/y and towards the high end of its target range), \(>26.1\%\) adj. operating margin (up at least 200bps y/y) and \(>6.0\%\) GAAP operating margins (up \(>800\) bps y/y).
